To check if a given string is a palindrome, you simply need to verify that it reads the same forwards as it does backward. Here are some examples of how to accomplish this in different programming languages.

1. Python
```python
def is_palindrome(s):
    return s == s[::-1]

print(is_palindrome('radar'))  # Output: True
```
2. Java
```java
public class Test {
    static boolean isPalindrome(String str) { 
        int start = 0;
        int end = str.length() - 1;
        while (start < end) { 
            if (str.charAt(start) != str.charAt(end)) { 
                return false; 
            }
            start++; 
            end--;
        }
        return true; 
    }
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        String str = "radar";
        if (isPalindrome(str)) {
            System.out.println("Yes, it is Palindrome"); 
        } else {
            System.out.println("No, it is not a Palindrome"); 
        }
    }
}
```
3. JavaScript
```JavaScript
function isPalindrome(str) {
    return str == str.split('').reverse().join('');
}

console.log(isPalindrome('radar'));  // Output: true
```
4. C#
```C#
public static bool IsPalindrome(string str){
    int left = 0;
    int right = str.Length - 1;

    while (left < right){
        if (str[left] != str[right]){
          return false;
        }

        left++;
        right--;
    }

    return true;
}
```
5. Ruby 
```ruby
def is_palindrome(str)
  str == str.reverse
end

puts is_palindrome('radar')  # Output: true
```
6. PHP
```php
function is_palindrome($str) {
